Higher (̴ 80%) cell viability, good biocompatibility, high stability under salt stress, negligible photo bleaching properties, good hydrophilicity and long term homogeneous phase maintenance of algal biomass derived CDs, made it suitable candidate for in vitro cell imaging. To determine their cell imaging application HEK-293 cells were treated with 50 μg mL−1 of A-NPCDs for 24 h. Fig. 6
                         showed intracellular uptake of A-NPCDs in HEK- 293 cell in dichromic (red and green) channel, supported by the merged images. However, cells were exogenously treated with 100 μM of Hg (II) and Cr (VI) solution, their fluorescence were quenched under red and green channel (Figs. 7 and 8

                        ). This observation strongly supported the quenching of fluorescence in presence of these toxic metal ions inside the living cells. Thus we expect that microalgal biomass derived carbon nanoprobe would be a suitable candidate for endogenous imaging of Hg (II) and Cr (VI) contaminated live cells.
